fields.description:
QUESTIONS

1. When did you first encounter English?
2. Since when have you been learning the language?
3. Have you ever been to an English-speaking country?
If yes, when – doing what – for how long?
If no, are you planning to go?
If you are planning to go, when – doing what – for how long?
4. What kind of activities do you do in English regularly (e.g. watch TV, see films, talk to people, write letters, e-mails …)?
5. What kind of reading do you do in English? (Please give some details: latest book you have read, newspapers, magazines etc.)
6. What do you expect to gain from doing this course? Are you doing this as part of your regular English Studies programme?
If yes, what made you decide to take up the subject „English‟ at university?
If no, why are you doing courses at the English Department?


INTRODUCTORY EXERCISE

- Please write a coherent text with the title "Why English?"

- It should include the answers to questions 1-6 above [see scanned original]. You are addressing your new teacher. Your intention is to provide with information about you and English, producing a kind of "learner autobiography".

- The purpose of this guided writing exercise is to find out more about your productive skills in English. You will receive comprehensive feedback on your work.

- Your piece of writing should be not less than a page. You have 30 minutes to do this exercise.

!! --> same task as "ILSS1_08W_Why_English"

fields.definition: Advanced Integrated Language Skills 2 = English for Academic Purposes “The content and structure of this course, in particular its assignments, are conceived specifically for students who are working on a research paper (an MA thesis or a seminar paper) in the same semester” (out of Vorlesungsverzeichnis)

Integrated Language and Study Skills 1

ILSS Aims:
- to upgrade your language and study skills, thereby providing support in an Englishmedium teaching environment 
- to encourage you to develop independent study habits (with regard to grammar, usage and
vocabulary)
- to identify and address deficiencies in your language competence

Outcomes:
You should be equipped to meet the language demands of your courses in literature, linguistics and cultural and regional studies. Should the occasion arise, you would probably be able to follow higher education courses in the Englishspeaking world (in fields familiar to you) or work in some Englishmedium contexts without undue strain.

Focus:
- study and research skills
- learning strategies
- language awareness
- vocabulary development
- reading and writing skills and subskills
- recognising and remedying errors in the use of the language system in writing and speaking
- introduction to formal / informal distinction, levels of formality and the concept of appropriateness

Assessment:
This will include attendance, active participation, class work, homework assignments and written tests on material covered. There is a Common Final Test (CFT) at the end of ILSS 2, modelled on the requirements for the International English Language Testing System (IELTS), Academic Module.

fields.content:
Actually, I haven't asked myself this question before. Maybe this is not a good sentence to start it all, but it is a good point to start thinking about how it all has started.

When I had my first english lesson, years ago, I was surprised, how interesting it was to talk in an other language. It was just something new, a rather new and funny experience at the age of 9.

We had this funny books called "Doodie" and from this time on I got more and more interested into this language.

Everybody told me, I am a "speaker". And somehow I knew that. I grew up with cratan, german and english and as I grew, my hobbies and interests did too. Some years later, at a higher level, my english class went to Ireland. I enjoyed the time there and also got more and more interested with literature and culture. In Ireland I decided to study english and german. There I saw what I really want. Not only that I fell in love with a country and their culture, past and history, also I knew that what I really want it how to teach and how I can improve my language. I wanted to learn how far I can go, this is what I am still doing. And now, here at the university. I also travel around a lot. Mostly to Ireland and the UK, but also to Croatia, Italy, Spain. I also prefer reading in English, would it be magazines, newspaper or books, I enjoy it. My favourite writers are Oscar Wilde, Frank McCourt and James Joyce, the last book I read was "The Portrait of the Artist as a young man" which I found was very interesting. I really love it how Joyce plays with words, it's gorgeous. I would never dare to write something like that, because I think that it would be rather bad. Actually, I haven't tried to write something poetical yet, but who knows, maybe one day.

What I am expecting from this course is to improve my english and maybe also to show me how to use words correctly.

I have so many ideas which I would really like to write them down, but I don't know how to do that, how to express myself in the correct way. There's a lot to learn, and a lot of what I want. Two years ago my german teacher showed me that there is a lot more in me that I have ever expected, maybe this is also why I am sitting here.

I am really glad studying english and german here and I am really looking forward to the future.

And I also guess that this is the worst text I've ever written about the fact why I study English.

The main strategy and secret for efficacious and successful studying is he time management; how students organise their time on study and free time during a school year.

To distinguish what is important in tasks you deal with, helps you to take control over your work.

The strategy of resolving the problems, approaching to the tasks controls your learning capability which brings you successive results.

To create the plan that fits you is very important and you should always stick to it.

Spending hours and hours on an intensive study without any plan and timetable usually will not bring a result you had in your vision at the beginning of your study.

Without a plan you are not able to divide time you should spend on your study and your basic human needs. You never know what it is important in tasks you are dealing with.

Where is the limit to achieve the goal you intended to? With no control over your work you will never know.
